@DATABASE "ppmquant.guide"
@INDEX "ImageEditor.guide/INDEX"
@FONT helvetica.font 13
@SMARTWRAP

@NODE MAIN "ImageEditor - Converter: ColorReduce [ppmquant]"
@TOC "Converter.guide/MAIN"

@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}ColorReduce@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{B}Quantize the colors in a portable pixmap down to a specified number.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{PAR}Reads a portable pixmap as input. Chooses ncolors to best represent the image,
maps the existing colors to the new ones, and writes a portable pixmap as output.@{LINE}
@{PAR}The quantization method is Heckbert's "median cut".@{LINE}
@{PAR}Alternately, you can skip the color-choosing step by specifying an entire colormap to be used.
The mapfile is just a ppm file; it can be any shape, all that matters is the colors in it and their order.@{LINE}
@{PAR}The Floyd-Steinberg error diffusion step gives vastly better results on images where the unmodified quantization has banding or other artifacts,
especially when going to a small number of colors. However, it does take substantially more CPU time.@{LINE}
@{PAR}See also @{" ColorDither " LINK "ppmdither.guide/MAIN"} and @{" Depth " LINK "pnmdepth.guide/MAIN"}.@{LINE}
@{PAR}[@{B}ppmquant@{UB}] @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Copyright (C) 1991 by Jef Poskanzer @{UI}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE
